          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Humans are prone to hyperuricaemia because they lack a specific enzyme that othe</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Humans are prone to hyperuricaemia because they lack a specific enzyme that other mammals possess. Which enzyme is absent in humans?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Xanthine oxidase</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Xanthine oxidase is present and active in humans — it is the enzyme that produces uric acid from xanthine. Inhibiting it with allopurinol is how we treat gout.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Uricase</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Most mammals have uricase, which converts uric acid to the highly soluble allantoin. Humans lack this enzyme, so uric acid is our final degradation product and accumulates in the blood.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Adenosine deaminase</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Adenosine deaminase converts adenosine to inosine in the purine degradation pathway. Its deficiency causes severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), not hyperuricaemia.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>HGPRT</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>HGPRT is a salvage pathway enzyme. Its complete deficiency causes Lesch-Nyhan syndrome with hyperuricaemia, but the reason all humans accumulate uric acid is the absence of uricase.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The correct answer is uricase. Unlike most mammals, humans cannot convert uric acid to allantoin because we lack uricase. This is the fundamental reason uric acid accumulates in our blood."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The absence of uricase means uric acid is the end product of purine metabolism in humans, making us uniquely susceptible to gout."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
