          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The Meselson-Stahl experiment confirmed that DNA replication is semi-conservativ</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The Meselson-Stahl experiment confirmed that DNA replication is semi-conservative. What does this mean?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Both strands of the parent DNA are preserved intact in one daughter molecule</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes conservative replication, where one daughter molecule would have both old strands and the other would be entirely new. Meselson-Stahl's density gradient results ruled this out.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Each daughter molecule contains one original strand and one newly synthesised strand</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! In semi-conservative replication, the two parental strands separate and each serves as a template. Every daughter molecule inherits one old strand paired with one new strand.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Short segments of old and new DNA alternate within each strand</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes dispersive replication, where old and new DNA would be interspersed throughout both strands. The Meselson-Stahl experiment eliminated this model after two generations of replication.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Only the leading strand is copied from the parent template</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both the leading and lagging strands are copied during replication. The leading strand is synthesised continuously, while the lagging strand is built in Okazaki fragments, but both use a parental template.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Semi-conservative means each daughter DNA molecule keeps one parental strand and gains one new strand. The Meselson-Stahl experiment proved this using density-labelled DNA across generations."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Semi-conservative replication ensures each daughter cell receives one original template strand, maintaining genetic fidelity across cell divisions."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
