          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In sickle cell anaemia, the codon GAG changes to GTG in the beta-globin gene, re</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In sickle cell anaemia, the codon GAG changes to GTG in the beta-globin gene, replacing glutamate with valine. What type of mutation is this?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Silent mutation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A silent mutation changes the codon but produces the same amino acid due to codon degeneracy. In sickle cell anaemia, the amino acid does change — from glutamate to valine — so it is not silent.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Nonsense mutation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A nonsense mutation creates a premature stop codon, truncating the protein. The GTG codon in sickle cell disease codes for valine, not a stop signal, so the full protein is still made — just with an altered amino acid.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Missense mutation</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! A missense mutation substitutes one amino acid for another. Here, GAG (glutamate) becomes GTG (valine). This single amino acid change causes haemoglobin S to polymerise under low oxygen, deforming red blood cells into a sickle shape.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Frameshift mutation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A frameshift mutation involves insertion or deletion of bases not in multiples of three, shifting the entire reading frame. Sickle cell anaemia involves a single base substitution (A→T) that does not alter the reading frame.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "This is a missense mutation: the single nucleotide change (A→T) replaces glutamate with valine. The reading frame is intact and no stop codon is created — only the identity of one amino acid changes."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly. Sickle cell anaemia is the classic example of a missense mutation — one base change, one amino acid swap, and a profoundly altered protein."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
