          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>CRISPR-Cas9 achieves precise gene editing by using a guide RNA to direct the Cas</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>CRISPR-Cas9 achieves precise gene editing by using a guide RNA to direct the Cas9 enzyme to a specific DNA target. What does Cas9 do once it reaches the target?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It adds a methyl group to silence the gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>DNA methylation is an epigenetic silencing mechanism, not gene editing. It does not alter the DNA sequence. Cas9 physically cuts the DNA strand rather than chemically modifying it.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It makes a double-strand cut in the DNA</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Cas9 is a nuclease that creates a double-strand break at the target site. The cell's own repair machinery then kicks in — either deleting the sequence, correcting it, or allowing insertion of new DNA at the cut site.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It amplifies the target sequence like PCR</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>PCR amplifies DNA using thermal cycling and Taq polymerase. CRISPR-Cas9 does not copy DNA — it cuts it at a precise location to enable editing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It binds a fluorescent probe to the target for visualisation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Fluorescent probe binding describes FISH (fluorescence in situ hybridisation), used for detecting chromosomal abnormalities. CRISPR-Cas9 cuts DNA for editing, not for visualisation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Cas9 is a nuclease — it makes a double-strand cut at the guide RNA's target site. The cell's repair machinery then processes the break, enabling gene deletion, correction, or insertion."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The double-strand break is the key event — it activates the cell's DNA repair pathways, which can then be harnessed to delete, correct, or insert genetic material."
                }
              ],
